---
/**
 * Entity chooser. The one question the S-corp pages could not answer, because
 * it needs the reader's own numbers: sole proprietor, S corporation or C
 * corporation.
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import EntityCalculator from '../../components/calculators/EntityCalculator.tsx';
import { CCORP_RATE } from '../../lib/entity';
---

<Base
  title="LLC vs S corp vs C corp calculator (2026)"
  description="Compare sole proprietor, S corporation and C corporation on your own numbers for 2026 — including what your state charges the company and the cost of running payroll."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Sole proprietor, S corp or C corp?</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Ranked on what you keep, not on what you pay.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Three structures, three completely different tax treatments. A sole proprietor pays self-employment
    tax on every dollar of profit. An S corporation splits the profit into salary and distribution, and
    only the salary carries payroll tax. A C corporation pays {(CCORP_RATE * 100).toFixed(0)}% on its own
    profit and then taxes you again on whatever you take out.
  </p>
  <p>
    That last point is why this asks how much you actually need to withdraw. Profit left inside a C
    corporation is taxed once, lightly. The same profit taken out is taxed twice. Every simplified
    comparison omits that input and then declares the C corporation either brilliant or useless.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>This ranks on take-home, deliberately</strong>
    <p>
      A C corporation can show the lowest tax simply by leaving your money inside the company. Ranking on
      tax paid would recommend it to someone who needs the cash to live on. So the comparison is on what
      reaches your pocket, and retained profit is reported separately rather than counted as income.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p class="section-label">Calculator</p>
  <EntityCalculator client:load />

  <h2>What the comparison includes that most do not</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>What your state charges the company.</strong> Four jurisdictions ignore the federal S election entirely; eighteen charge a minimum owed even at a loss. That is often larger than the federal saving.</li>
    <li><strong>The cost of running payroll.</strong> An S corporation needs payroll and a separate return. It is a real annual cost and it is the reason the election does not pay at low profit.</li>
    <li><strong>Both halves of payroll tax.</strong> An owner-operator bears the employer half as well, because it comes out of the same profit.</li>
    <li><strong>Charges that cannot be computed here</strong> — a gross receipts tax needs turnover, a net worth tax needs a balance sheet — are listed rather than silently dropped.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/">S-corp election by state</a></li>
    <li><a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/salary/">What salary to pay yourself</a></li>
    <li><a href="/1099-tax-calculator/">1099 taxes by state</a></li>
